# [FCP2] Sandbox + Egress Proxy: NetworkConstraints, Secret Injection, OS/WASI Profiles

## Goal
Make connectors safe by default:
- filesystem and process sandboxing
- deny-by-default networking
- capability-gated Network Guard (egress proxy) enforcing NetworkConstraints
- secret injection without persisting secrets to disk

## Recommended Sandbox Stack (2025-2026)

| Component | Technology | Notes |
|-----------|------------|-------|
| WASI Runtime | `wasmtime` 29+ | WASI Preview 2 / Component Model |
| Linux Sandbox | `seccomp-bpf` + `namespaces` | Landlock 5.0+ when available |
| macOS Sandbox | `sandbox-exec` (seatbelt) | App Sandbox profiles |
| Windows Sandbox | `AppContainer` | Low-integrity token isolation |
| Secret Handling | `zeroize` 1.8+ | Memory zeroing on drop |
| Egress Proxy | `hyper` 1.6+ + `tokio` 1.44+ | HTTP/TCP proxy |

## Required Behaviors (Spec-Aligned)

### Sandbox Profiles
Support the manifest-defined sandbox profiles:
- `strict`, `strict_plus`, `moderate`, `permissive`

Core invariants:
- In `strict`/`moderate`, connectors MUST NOT have raw outbound sockets
- Networking is mediated by the MeshNode Network Guard and authorized by capabilities + constraints

```rust
/// Manifest-defined sandbox profile
pub enum SandboxProfile {
    /// No network, no filesystem beyond temp
    Strict,
    /// Strict + limited approved hostcalls
    StrictPlus { allowed_hostcalls: Vec<String> },
    /// Network via proxy only, limited filesystem
    Moderate { allowed_paths: Vec<PathBuf> },
    /// Less restricted, for legacy/trusted connectors
    Permissive,
}
```

### NetworkConstraints (Deny-by-Default)
NetworkConstraints MUST enforce:
- host allow-list + port allow-list
- canonicalize hostnames (lowercase, IDNA2008, strip trailing dot)
- deny IP literals unless explicitly allowed
- deny localhost / RFC1918 / link-local / tailnet ranges by default
- DNS resolution through a policy-checked resolver
- TLS rules: require SNI match; optional SPKI pin verification

```rust
/// Network constraint evaluation
pub struct NetworkConstraints {
    pub hosts: Vec<HostPattern>,       // *.example.com, api.stripe.com
    pub ports: Vec<PortRange>,         // 443, 8000-9000
    pub allow_ip_literals: bool,       // default: false
    pub allow_private_ranges: bool,    // default: false
    pub tls: TlsConstraints,
}

pub struct TlsConstraints {
    pub require_tls: bool,             // default: true
    pub require_sni_match: bool,       // default: true
    pub spki_pins: Vec<SpkiPin>,       // optional pinning
    pub min_version: TlsVersion,       // default: 1.2
}
```

### Network Guard (Egress Proxy)
The proxy MUST support:
- HTTP/HTTPS requests with header injection
- raw TCP connect (for database/queue connectors) while still enforcing constraints
- WebSocket upgrade with constraint validation

